title: Peace Key from Reading, Pennsylvania
creator: RR
description: Ceremonial key to the city of Reading, Pennsylvania. Given to activists by the city mayor during the Great Peace March for Global Nuclear Disarmament in 1986. Brass key with a pretzel-shaped handle, engravings on the key read "Reading, PA" , " 'The Pretzel Capital of the World' " on one side, and "Mayor Karen A. Miller" on the other.
image_alt_text: A key from the city of Reading, PA

title: Barometer from the Golden Rule
creator: RR
description: In 1958, the Golden Rule sailed towards the Marshall Islands to protest nuclear weapons testing. It was the first boat that attempted to disrupt a nuclear test, and this action created publicity and further protests against nuclear testing in the pacific. This barometer from the voyage comes from the Albert Bigelow Papers (DG 076). Bigelow was the captain of the Golden Rule. It is a metal cylinder with a glass face on top. Around the barometer's circular face are numbers to indicate the air pressure; there is writing around the top that says "Stormy", "Rain", "Change", "Fair", and "Very Dry" in capital letters and various fonts. Small lettering in the middle and bottom of the face reads "Selsi", "Holosteric Barometer" , "Copyright 1940 Selsi Co. Inc." and Made in France."

title: Jane Addams' Nobel Peace Prize
creator: RR
description: The Nobel Peace Prize was awarded to Jane Addams in 1931 for her lifelong dedication to international relations and disarmament. She was the first American woman to receive the honor. The medal comes with a dark green box with the inscription "Nobel Fredspris 1931, Jane Addams. On one side of the medal is Alfred Nobel's profile in relief; his name and the years of his birth and death are encircled in Roman numerals around his face. The other side displays three naked men embracing, they are surrounded by the Latin words "Pro pace et fraternitate gentium" (For peace and fraternity among peoples).
